    <item>
      <title>Building a Concept Lattice by Hand</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/order/texts/building-a-concept-lattice-by-hand/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 31 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/order/texts/building-a-concept-lattice-by-hand/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;This tutorial walks through building a &lt;a href=&#34;../terms/concept-lattice.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;concept lattice&lt;/a&gt; from a small data table. You need no mathematical background — just the ability to look at a table and find patterns.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;the-data&#34;&gt;The data&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Suppose you have five files with frontmatter:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;table&gt;&#xA;  &lt;thead&gt;&#xA;      &lt;tr&gt;&#xA;          &lt;th&gt;File&lt;/th&gt;&#xA;          &lt;th&gt;type&lt;/th&gt;&#xA;          &lt;th&gt;authors&lt;/th&gt;&#xA;          &lt;th&gt;status&lt;/th&gt;&#xA;          &lt;th&gt;extends&lt;/th&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/tr&gt;&#xA;  &lt;/thead&gt;&#xA;  &lt;tbody&gt;&#xA;      &lt;tr&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;A&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;paper&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;emsenn&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;draft&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;—&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/tr&gt;&#xA;      &lt;tr&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;B&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;paper&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;emsenn&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;published&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;lattice&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/tr&gt;&#xA;      &lt;tr&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;C&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;term&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;emsenn&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;published&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;—&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/tr&gt;&#xA;      &lt;tr&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;D&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;paper&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;claude&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;draft&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;lattice&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/tr&gt;&#xA;      &lt;tr&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;E&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;term&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;—&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;draft&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;—&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/tr&gt;&#xA;  &lt;/tbody&gt;&#xA;&lt;/table&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The files are the &lt;strong&gt;objects&lt;/strong&gt;. The attribute-value pairs are the &lt;strong&gt;attributes&lt;/strong&gt;. (For simplicity, treat each column as binary: does the file have a value for this attribute or not?)&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>What Distributivity Buys You</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/order/texts/what-distributivity-buys-you/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 31 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/order/texts/what-distributivity-buys-you/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Not all &lt;a href=&#34;../terms/lattice.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;lattices&lt;/a&gt; are &lt;a href=&#34;../../algebra/terms/distributivity.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;distributive&lt;/a&gt;. But the ones that matter most in practice are. Here is what distributivity gives you.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;the-law&#34;&gt;The law&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;A lattice is distributive if &lt;a href=&#34;../terms/meet.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;meet&lt;/a&gt; distributes over &lt;a href=&#34;../terms/join.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;join&lt;/a&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34; display=&#34;block&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∧&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∨&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∧&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∨&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∧&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;a \wedge (b \vee c) = (a \wedge b) \vee (a \wedge c)&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;p&gt;This says: narrowing down (&lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∧&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\wedge&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;) a choice between &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;b&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; and &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;c&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; (&lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∨&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\vee&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;) is the same as choosing between the narrowed-down versions. The order of operations does not matter.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;In a non-distributive lattice, this can fail. There exist lattices where &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∧&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∨&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;≠&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∧&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∨&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∧&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;a \wedge (b \vee c) \neq (a \wedge b) \vee (a \wedge c)&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; — narrowing a choice gives a different result from choosing between narrowed options. This makes reasoning about the lattice harder because you cannot freely rearrange meet and join.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>What Galois Connections Do</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/order/texts/what-galois-connections-do/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 31 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/order/texts/what-galois-connections-do/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;A &lt;a href=&#34;../terms/galois-connection.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;Galois connection&lt;/a&gt; is a pair of maps between two ordered sets, where each map partially undoes the other.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;the-idea&#34;&gt;The idea&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Suppose you have two collections — say, a set of people and a set of skills — with a relation between them (who has which skill). You can ask two questions:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Given a group of people, what skills do ALL of them share?&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Given a group of skills, which people have ALL of them?&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;These two questions define two maps. The first goes from subsets of people to subsets of skills. The second goes from subsets of skills to subsets of people. They go in opposite directions, and they are connected: the more people you include, the fewer skills they all share. The more skills you require, the fewer people qualify.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>What Is a Lattice?</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/order/texts/what-is-a-lattice/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 30 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/order/texts/what-is-a-lattice/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;A &lt;a href=&#34;./what-is-a-partial-order.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;partial order&lt;/a&gt; lets you compare things. A lattice guarantees that comparisons always produce results.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Given two elements &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;a&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; and &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;b&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; in a partial order, you can ask: what is the most you can say that is true of both? And: what is the least you can say that covers both? In a lattice, these questions always have answers.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;meet&lt;/strong&gt; of &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;a&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; and &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;b&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; (written &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∧&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;a \wedge b&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;) is their greatest lower bound: the largest element that is below both &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;a&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; and &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;b&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. Think of it as &amp;ldquo;what &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;a&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; and &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;b&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; agree on.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>What Is a Partial Order?</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/order/texts/what-is-a-partial-order/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 30 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/order/texts/what-is-a-partial-order/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;You already know what &amp;ldquo;less than&amp;rdquo; means for numbers: 3 is less than 7, and 7 is less than 10, and therefore 3 is less than 10. You also know that nothing is less than itself in the strict sense, but everything is &amp;ldquo;less than or equal to&amp;rdquo; itself.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;A partial order takes these intuitions and applies them to anything, not just numbers. A partial order on a set is a relation &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≤&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\leq&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; satisfying three conditions:&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Closure Operators and Fixed Points</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/order/texts/closure-operators/</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 01 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/order/texts/closure-operators/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;entry-conditions&#34;&gt;Entry conditions&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Use &lt;a href=&#34;../../../concepts/closure-operator/index.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;closure operators&lt;/a&gt; when you have:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;A &lt;a href=&#34;../terms/partial-order.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;partially ordered&lt;/a&gt; set (or complete &lt;a href=&#34;../terms/lattice.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;lattice&lt;/a&gt;) of structures.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;A process that enlarges or completes a structure in a canonical way.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;A need to find the smallest structure that is &amp;ldquo;closed&amp;rdquo; — stable under the process.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;definitions&#34;&gt;Definitions&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;A &lt;strong&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;../../../concepts/closure-operator/index.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;closure operator&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; on a &lt;a href=&#34;../terms/partial-order.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;partially ordered&lt;/a&gt; set &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;P&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≤&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;(P, \leq)&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; is a function &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;:&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;P&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;→&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;P&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;c : P \to P&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; satisfying three properties [@davey_IntroductionLatticesOrder_2002; @erne_ClosureOperators_2009]:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;ol&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Extensive&lt;/strong&gt; (inflationary): &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≤&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;x \leq c(x)&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; for all &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;x&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. The closure of &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;x&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; is at least as large as &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;x&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Monotone&lt;/strong&gt;: if &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≤&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;y&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;x \leq y&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; then &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≤&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;y&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;c(x) \leq c(y)&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. Larger inputs produce larger outputs.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Idempotent&lt;/strong&gt;: &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;c(c(x)) = c(x)&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; for all &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;x&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. Closing a closed element does nothing further.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ol&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;An element &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;x&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; is &lt;strong&gt;closed&lt;/strong&gt; (or &lt;strong&gt;stable&lt;/strong&gt;) if &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;c(x) = x&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. The set of closed elements is denoted &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;F&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;i&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;{&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∈&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;P&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;:&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;x&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;}&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\mathrm{Fix}(c) = \{x \in P : c(x) = x\}&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Heyting Algebras</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/order/texts/heyting-algebras/</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 01 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/order/texts/heyting-algebras/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;entry-conditions&#34;&gt;Entry conditions&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Use &lt;a href=&#34;../../../concepts/heyting-algebra/index.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;Heyting algebras&lt;/a&gt; when you can:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Start from a &lt;a href=&#34;../terms/lattice.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;lattice&lt;/a&gt; with top &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;⊤&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\top&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; and bottom &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;⊥&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\bot&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Define an implication operation &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⇒&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;a \Rightarrow b&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; for every pair of elements.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Accept that some elements may lack complements — &lt;a href=&#34;../../../../../../humanities/domains/philosophy/terms/law-of-excluded-middle.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;excluded middle&lt;/a&gt; may fail.&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;definitions&#34;&gt;Definitions&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;A &lt;strong&gt;bounded &lt;a href=&#34;../terms/lattice.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;lattice&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; is a &lt;a href=&#34;../terms/lattice.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;lattice&lt;/a&gt; with a greatest element &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;⊤&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\top&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; and a least element &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;⊥&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\bot&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;A &lt;strong&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;../../../../../../humanities/domains/general/domains/people/arend-heyting.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;Heyting&lt;/a&gt; algebra&lt;/strong&gt; [@esakia_HeytingAlgebras_2019] is a bounded &lt;a href=&#34;../terms/lattice.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;lattice&lt;/a&gt; &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;H&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≤&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∧&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∨&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;⊥&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;⊤&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;(H, \leq, \wedge, \vee, \bot, \top)&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; equipped with a binary operation &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⇒&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\Rightarrow&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; (called &lt;a href=&#34;../../../disciplines/logic/terms/heyting-implication.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;Heyting implication&lt;/a&gt;) satisfying:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34; display=&#34;block&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≤&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;(&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;⇒&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo stretchy=&#34;false&#34;&gt;)&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mspace width=&#34;1em&#34;/&gt;&lt;mtext&gt;iff&lt;/mtext&gt;&lt;mspace width=&#34;1em&#34;/&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∧&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≤&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;&#xA;c \leq (a \Rightarrow b) \quad \text{iff} \quad c \wedge a \leq b&#xA;&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;p&gt;for all &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo separator=&#34;true&#34;&gt;,&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∈&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;H&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;a, b, c \in H&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Lattices</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/order/texts/lattices/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/order/texts/lattices/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;what-this-lesson-covers&#34;&gt;What this lesson covers&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;This lesson introduces &lt;a href=&#34;../terms/lattice.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;lattices&lt;/a&gt;: &lt;a href=&#34;../terms/partial-order.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;partially ordered&lt;/a&gt; sets where every pair of elements has a greatest lower bound (meet) and a least upper bound (join). By the end, you will be able to determine whether a poset is a &lt;a href=&#34;../terms/lattice.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;lattice&lt;/a&gt;, compute meets and joins, and recognize bounded and complete &lt;a href=&#34;../terms/lattice.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;lattices&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;why-it-matters&#34;&gt;Why it matters&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;A &lt;a href=&#34;../terms/partial-order.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;partial order&lt;/a&gt; lets you say &amp;ldquo;this is below that,&amp;rdquo; but it does not guarantee you can combine two elements. Given two topics in a library — say &lt;em&gt;Modal Logic&lt;/em&gt; and &lt;em&gt;Set Theory&lt;/em&gt; — a &lt;a href=&#34;../terms/partial-order.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;partial order&lt;/a&gt; under &amp;ldquo;is more specific than&amp;rdquo; tells you they are both below &lt;em&gt;Mathematics&lt;/em&gt;. But is there a most specific topic that encompasses both? Is there a most general topic that both encompass?&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Partial Orders</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/order/texts/orders/</link>
      <pubDate>Fri, 26 Dec 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/math/domains/order/texts/orders/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h2 id=&#34;what-this-lesson-covers&#34;&gt;What this lesson covers&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;This lesson introduces &lt;a href=&#34;../terms/partial-order.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;partial orders&lt;/a&gt;: the mathematical structure that captures the idea of &amp;ldquo;this thing is at least as much as that thing&amp;rdquo; in a consistent way. By the end, you will be able to identify when a relation is a &lt;a href=&#34;../terms/partial-order.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;partial order&lt;/a&gt;, draw its Hasse diagram, and explain why &lt;a href=&#34;../terms/partial-order.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;partial orders&lt;/a&gt; matter for the structures that follow (&lt;a href=&#34;../terms/lattice.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;lattices&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&#34;../../../concepts/heyting-algebra/index.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;Heyting algebras&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&#34;../../../concepts/closure-operator/index.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;closure operators&lt;/a&gt;).&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;why-it-matters&#34;&gt;Why it matters&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Suppose you are organizing a library. You could sort books alphabetically — a total order where every pair of books has a definite ranking. But suppose instead you want to organize by topic. &lt;em&gt;Introduction to Logic&lt;/em&gt; is more specific than &lt;em&gt;Mathematics&lt;/em&gt;, and &lt;em&gt;Modal Logic&lt;/em&gt; is more specific than &lt;em&gt;Introduction to Logic&lt;/em&gt;. But how does &lt;em&gt;Modal Logic&lt;/em&gt; compare to &lt;em&gt;Set Theory&lt;/em&gt;? They are both more specific than &lt;em&gt;Mathematics&lt;/em&gt;, but neither is more specific than the other. They are incomparable.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
  </channel>
</rss>
